 Following the #OscarsSoWhite backlash which trended recently, the Academy of Motion Pictures Arts and Sciences, better known as The Oscars, has revealed its 2019 invitees featuring over 800 people, half of them women. This year’s list features three Nigerians who have stood themselves out in the art of filmmaking. The three invited personalities are iconic director, Tunde Kelani, actor Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje and writer Chinonye Chukwu. Better known as TK, Kelani, a legendary filmmaker, director and cinematographer is famed for his high-quality productions and thematic movies. Since the release of ‘Orun Mooru’, his first film in 1982, Kelani has gone on to make over 15 movies, most of which were produced via his production company, Mainframe Films and Television Productions, which he started in 1991. Over the years, he has become well known for his film adaptions. His popular literary adaptions include ‘Thunderbolt: Magun’ (adapted from Adebayo Faleti’s ‘The Whore’) and ‘Dazzling Mirage’ (Olayinka Abimbola Egbokhare’s novel of the same name). Kelani is currently working on the film adaptation of Wole Soyinka’s award-winning play, ‘The Lion and the Jewel’. Fellow invitee, Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje, is a British-Nigerian actor who has made a name for himself in several critically acclaimed movies and TV shows. The list includes ‘The Bourne Identity’, ‘Thor: The Dark World’, ‘Suicide Squad’, ‘Game of Thrones’, ‘Lost’ and a host of others. He made his directorial debut at the 2018 Toronto International Film Festival with the auto-biographical ‘Farming’. Also invited is Chinonye Chukwu, a Nigerian-American filmmaker who made history by becoming the first black woman to win the Sundance Film Festival’s biggest prize. She won the Grand Jury Prize for her movie, ‘Clemency’ which she both wrote and directed. The Academy of Motion Pictures Arts and Sciences invited 842 members to join the Oscars organization, parading people from 59 countries including Nigeria. The post Thre